content:
Le spectre de la «défaite historique» hante encore les gauches alternatives

Près de 10 ans après les percées de #Syriza en Grèce et #Podemos en Espagne, que reste-t-il des percées électorales à la gauche de la social-démocratie? Un ressac dramatique, qui épargne encore la France mais interroge les stratégies poursuivies et la crédibilité d’une voie électorale vers le changement social.

content: For my own part, I dealt with a lot of unresolved trauma, that suddenly and violently surfaced in my late 20's and early 30's. It started as attacks that I didn't understand at the time, was anxiety and intense panic attacks, that would often last for days. I went to the doctor and ended up in the ER several times, but they found nothing but a few unrelated health issues. I got to the point where I was afraid to leave the house, because I didn't know when an attack would strike. After doing a lot of research, and talking to friends and family, I finally understood that it was anxiety and panic attacks, but now I felt weak and out of control. Why couldn't I just get ahold of myself? My little brother who had been through a lot of anxiety and panic attacks himself started talking to me, we talked about family stuff that I had pushed down or "forgotten" for years. I had always allowed myself to think that my childhood was rough, but not really abusive, suddenly I was having to face that it actually was. I had just been taught to make excuses for people my whole life and be an adult when I was only a child. I was taught my feelings didn't matter, and suddenly I was feeling everything. Honestly, this made everything with the anxiety and panic worse for awhile, but when I started retreating more my brother said No, you can't hide you have to face this, and I knew he was right, even though I was really scared. I started going out again, even though I'd often be trembling and terrified, and I did have panic attacks in public, and it did suck. Over time it got easier though, I started recognizing what it felt like when they were coming on and how I needed to change my breathing, and when I needed to take a moment for myself. I'm not here to say that I don't deal with anxiety and panic attacks anymore, I certainly do, but for me, facing my fears head on actually worked.
